👉 Spring Boot is a tool built on top of Spring that makes it fast and easy to create Spring applications.

⚡ Spring Boot Solves This

👉 With Spring Boot:
- No XML ❌
- Minimal configuration ✅
- Built-in server (Tomcat) ✅
- Ready-to-run app ✅

🧩 What Spring Boot Gives You
1. Auto Configuration
👉 You don’t configure everything manually

Example:
spring.datasource.url=...

👉 Spring Boot configures DB automatically

2. Starter Dependencies
Instead of adding many dependencies:

spring-boot-starter-web

👉 Adds everything needed for web apps

3. Embedded Server
👉 No need to install Tomcat separately
Just run:
mvn spring-boot:run

4. Production Ready Features
- Logging
- Monitoring
- Health checks

🚀 What is @SpringBootApplication?
👉 It’s a single annotation that combines 3 important annotations

"It tells Spring Boot to start the app, scan components, and auto-configure everything.”

It is combination of :
1️. @Configuration = This class contains bean definitions

2. @ComponentScan = Scan this package and sub-packages for beans
So Spring finds:
@Component
@Service
@Repository
@Controller

3. @EnableAutoConfiguration
👉 Means:
“Spring Boot automatically configures things for you”
Example:
Database config
Web server
JSON setup


⚙️ What Happens When You Run This
SpringApplication.run(DemoApplication.class, args);

👉 Spring Boot:
1. Starts Spring container
2. Scans all components
3. Creates beans
4. Injects dependencies
5. Applies auto-configuration
6. Starts server (Tomcat)


---------------------------------------------------------------------

Q.1 What is starter dependencies and what is "opinionated setup" mean?
Ans: Starter Dependencies : Pre-configured dependency bundles
You add one dependency → Spring Boot automatically includes all required libraries
📌 Example:
spring-boot-starter-web
→ includes:
Spring MVC
Jackson (JSON)
Embedded Tomcat
👉 No need to add everything manually

Opinionated setup : Spring Boot decides default configurations for you
You don’t need to configure everything — Spring Boot assumes best defaults
📌 Example:
Auto setup for server
Default project structure
Auto DB config

Q.2 What is application.properties?
Ans: A file where you configure your Spring Boot application

Example:
server.port=8081
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/mydb
spring.datasource.username=postgres
spring.datasource.password=1234

Q.3 What is application.yml?
Ans: Same purpose as application.properties but having cleaner format

Example:
server:
  port: 8081

spring:
  datasource:
    url: jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/mydb
    username: postgres
    password: 1234

Q.4 What is CommandLineRunner?
Ans: It is an interface that runs after Spring Boot starts

Example:
@Component
public class MyRunner implements CommandLineRunner {

    @Override
    public void run(String... args) {
        System.out.println("App started!");
    }
}

Q.5 What is ApplicationRunner?
Ans: Same purpose — runs after app starts but handles arguments differently

Example:
@Component
public class MyRunner implements ApplicationRunner {

    @Override
    public void run(ApplicationArguments args) {
        System.out.println("App started!");
    }
}

| Feature     | CommandLineRunner | ApplicationRunner      |
| ----------- | ----------------- | ---------------------- |
| Arguments   | `String[] args`   | `ApplicationArguments` |
| Flexibility | Basic             | More powerful          |


*************************************************************************************

Spring Boot me rest apis kese banti hai:

1. @RestController
@RestController
public class UserController {
}

👉 Bolta hai:
“Ye class API handle karegi”

2. Endpoint (URL banana)
@GetMapping("/hello")
public String hello() {
    return "Hello Bhai 😄";
}

👉 Browser me:
http://localhost:8080/hello

👉 Output:
Hello Bhai 😄

Full CRUD Example:

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {

    @GetMapping
    public String getUsers() {
        return "All users";
    }

    @PostMapping
    public String createUser() {
        return "User created";
    }

    @PutMapping("/{id}")
    public String updateUser(@PathVariable int id) {
        return "User updated " + id;
    }

    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
    public String deleteUser(@PathVariable int id) {
        return "User deleted " + id;
    }
}


Important Concepts
📌 @PathVariable
@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
👉 URL se data lena

📌 @RequestParam
@GetMapping("/users?name=Pulkit")

📌 @RequestBody
@PostMapping
public User create(@RequestBody User user)
👉 JSON → Java object


Steps how api flows working in spring boot:

1️. Client Request
👉 Browser / Postman hit karta hai:
GET /users

2. Embedded Tomcat Server
👉 Spring Boot ka built-in server (Tomcat) request receive karta hai
Request → Tomcat

3️. DispatcherServlet (MOST IMPORTANT 🔥)
👉 Ye front controller hai (boss of Spring MVC)
Tomcat → DispatcherServlet

👉 Kaam:
Decide karega request kahan bhejni hai

4️. Handler Mapping
👉 DispatcherServlet puchta hai:

“Is URL /users ko kaun handle karega?”
DispatcherServlet → HandlerMapping

👉 Ye find karta hai:
@GetMapping("/users")

5️. Controller Call
HandlerMapping → UserController
👉 Controller method run hota hai

@GetMapping("/users")
public List<User> getUsers() {
    return userService.getUsers();
}

6️. Service Layer
Controller → Service
👉 Business logic

7️. Repository Layer
Service → Repository
👉 DB call

8️. Database
Repository → DB → data
🔄 Response Flow Back
DB → Repository → Service → Controller → DispatcherServlet → Tomcat → Client

9️ JSON Conversion (IMPORTANT)
👉 Controller jo return karta hai:
return List<User>

👉 Spring automatically convert karta hai → JSON (Jackson use karke)

Client
 ↓
Tomcat
 ↓
DispatcherServlet
 ↓
HandlerMapping
 ↓
Controller
 ↓
Service
 ↓
Repository
 ↓
Database

⬆ same path se response back

***********************************************************************************

Kuch annotations:

1. @PathVariable
👉 URL ke andar jo dynamic value hoti hai usko lene ke liye

Example:
@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public String getUser(@PathVariable int id) {
    return "User id: " + id;
}

👉 Request:
GET /users/10
👉 Output:
User id: 10

2. @RequestParam
👉 Query parameters (URL ke ? ke baad wale data)

Example:
@GetMapping("/users")
public String getUser(@RequestParam String name) {
    return "User: " + name;
}

👉 Request:
GET /users?name=Pulkit
👉 Output:
User: Pulkit

3. @RequestBody
👉 Frontend se aane wala JSON → Java object

Example:
@PostMapping("/users")
public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
    return user;
}

👉 Request:
{
  "name": "Pulkit",
  "email": "abc@gmail.com"
}

📌 4. @RequestHeader
👉 HTTP headers se value lene ke liye

Example:
@GetMapping("/test")
public String getHeader(@RequestHeader("User-Agent") String agent) {
    return agent;
}

👉 Use:
Auth tokens
Metadata

**************************************************************************************************

1. Exception Handling Kya Hai?
👉 Jab error aaye (user not found, etc.)
→ Instead of manual if-else
→ Exception throw karte hain

👉 Aur ek jagah handle karte hain (global)

2. Logging Kya Hai?
👉 System.out.println ❌ (bad practice)
👉 Proper logging use karo ✅

Uses:
- Debugging
- Error tracking
- Production monitoring


STEP 1: Custom Exception Bana

package puki.demo.springbootfirst;

public class UserNotFoundException extends RuntimeException {
    public UserNotFoundException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}


STEP 2: Global Exception Handler

package puki.demo.springbootfirst;

import org.springframework.http.HttpStatus;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;

@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    @ExceptionHandler(UserNotFoundException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleUserNotFound(UserNotFoundException ex) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND).body(ex.getMessage());
    }

    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleGeneral(Exception ex) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR)
                .body("Something went wrong");
    }
}


STEP 3: Logging Add Kar (IMPORTANT)

import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

